1
00:00:00,649 --> 00:00:04,219
Speaker 14: Hello everyone,
and welcome to CON42 Golang.

2
00:00:04,969 --> 00:00:09,119
I am Sonali, creative design
director at LB Networks, and over

3
00:00:09,119 --> 00:00:13,630
the next fifteen minutes or so, I
want to talk about something that

4
00:00:13,630 --> 00:00:17,729
sits right at the intersection of
design and platform engineering.

5
00:00:18,409 --> 00:00:22,819
How we build design systems
that actually hold up inside

6
00:00:22,860 --> 00:00:25,659
high-performance analytics platforms.

7
00:00:26,159 --> 00:00:31,570
If you have ever shipped UI in front
of a Go-powered backend that's slicing

8
00:00:31,570 --> 00:00:35,780
through millions of rows in real
time, you already know the problem.

9
00:00:36,469 --> 00:00:38,539
The backend scales beautifully.

10
00:00:38,960 --> 00:00:41,010
The front end, not always.

11
00:00:41,559 --> 00:00:46,180
Components drift, teams duplicate
work, and what started as a clean

12
00:00:46,180 --> 00:00:50,750
design systems slowly turns into
a five slightly different ones.

13
00:00:51,590 --> 00:00:56,449
So today, I want to walk you through
the architectural foundations I

14
00:00:56,449 --> 00:00:59,100
think every team needs to get right.

15
00:00:59,879 --> 00:01:06,189
Five measurable pillars that together
make a beautiful design system reliable,

16
00:01:06,189 --> 00:01:11,280
accessible, and performant across
distributed teams and diverse interfaces.

17
00:01:11,790 --> 00:01:13,269
So let's get into it.

18
00:01:13,769 --> 00:01:15,959
Let's start with the problem first.

19
00:01:16,919 --> 00:01:21,559
Enterprise analytics platforms have
to serve a lot of people at once.

20
00:01:22,209 --> 00:01:26,759
Multiple teams, multiple surfaces,
multiple product context, all running

21
00:01:26,759 --> 00:01:32,059
at the same time, all expected to
feel like one coherent product.

22
00:01:32,529 --> 00:01:36,789
And without a principal system
underneath, fragmentation compounds,

23
00:01:37,019 --> 00:01:38,879
and it compounds really fast.

24
00:01:39,379 --> 00:01:42,309
There are three patterns
I see almost everywhere.

25
00:01:42,769 --> 00:01:45,609
The first is inconsistency.

26
00:01:46,269 --> 00:01:50,989
Components diverge across teams because
there's no shared source of truth.

27
00:01:51,489 --> 00:01:56,929
So the button on one dashboard doesn't
quite look like the button in another

28
00:01:56,929 --> 00:02:02,479
dashboard, and the chart on page A behaves
very different from the chart on page B.

29
00:02:02,979 --> 00:02:04,679
Second is duplication.

30
00:02:05,179 --> 00:02:09,469
Parallel implementation create
maintenance debt and version drift.

31
00:02:09,889 --> 00:02:13,469
Three teams end up building the
same filter panel three different

32
00:02:13,469 --> 00:02:17,749
ways, and now you're maintaining
three slightly broken version of

33
00:02:17,799 --> 00:02:19,829
each one of them at the same time.

34
00:02:20,509 --> 00:02:23,759
And the third is the governance gaps.

35
00:02:24,259 --> 00:02:28,889
There's no clear process for contribution,
no clear standard for review, no

36
00:02:28,889 --> 00:02:31,299
enforcement around accessibility.

37
00:02:31,819 --> 00:02:35,359
Things get added, but
nothing ever gets retired.

38
00:02:35,899 --> 00:02:39,449
So quality slips over time, and slowly.

39
00:02:39,949 --> 00:02:45,874
So these three problems that
I just described are not very

40
00:02:46,484 --> 00:02:48,694
Complicated or dramatic on day one.

41
00:02:49,584 --> 00:02:54,514
But they do compound as you follow
the same pattern over and over.

42
00:02:55,394 --> 00:02:59,734
And the bigger your platform gets, the
more expensive they actually become.

43
00:03:00,234 --> 00:03:04,624
So how do we solve this in a
way that actually holds up?

44
00:03:05,124 --> 00:03:10,574
I think a reliable design system
for analytics platforms resets

45
00:03:10,574 --> 00:03:16,084
on five measurable interconnected
foundation, which are five pillars.

46
00:03:16,584 --> 00:03:22,494
Component modularity, which is basically
decoupled UI primitives that let teams

47
00:03:22,494 --> 00:03:24,654
build in parallel without colliding.

48
00:03:25,154 --> 00:03:28,484
Token-driven theming, a single
source of truth for every

49
00:03:28,484 --> 00:03:30,224
visual property in the system.

50
00:03:30,724 --> 00:03:35,094
Cross-platform consistency,
coherence across dashboards, embedded

51
00:03:35,424 --> 00:03:37,724
analytics and operational tools.

52
00:03:38,694 --> 00:03:43,124
Versioning discipline, semantic
releases that evolve the system without

53
00:03:43,124 --> 00:03:45,944
breaking everyone who depends on it.

54
00:03:46,874 --> 00:03:53,424
And finally, governance matur-maturity,
sustainable workflows that scale

55
00:03:54,054 --> 00:03:56,144
autonomy and alignment together.

56
00:03:56,644 --> 00:04:01,744
So I want to walk you through
each of these pillars and show

57
00:04:01,744 --> 00:04:03,534
you what makes them actually work.

58
00:04:04,514 --> 00:04:08,874
Pillar one is component modularity,
and this is the core principle.

59
00:04:09,594 --> 00:04:13,794
Decoupled UI primitives are the foundation
of any maintainable design system.

60
00:04:14,474 --> 00:04:16,144
So the idea is very simple.

61
00:04:16,734 --> 00:04:21,434
When components own their own behavior,
their own styling, and their own API

62
00:04:21,434 --> 00:04:26,434
contract, teams can build independently
without stepping on each other.

63
00:04:26,934 --> 00:04:31,314
The way I like to think about it
is layered model with three levels.

64
00:04:31,844 --> 00:04:36,154
At the bottom, you have primitives,
the atoms, buttons, inputs,

65
00:04:36,154 --> 00:04:38,404
the small decoupled UI pieces.

66
00:04:38,904 --> 00:04:41,844
In the middle, you have
composite components.

67
00:04:42,514 --> 00:04:44,814
These are composed elements with behavior.

68
00:04:44,814 --> 00:04:50,314
For example a search input that combines
an icon, a text field, and a clear button.

69
00:04:51,304 --> 00:04:54,534
A card that combines a
header, body, and actions.

70
00:04:55,034 --> 00:04:57,904
And at the top, you have feature modules.

71
00:04:58,114 --> 00:05:04,354
These are feature-level pieces that
orchestrate composite components into

72
00:05:04,354 --> 00:05:06,444
something which is domain-specific.

73
00:05:06,944 --> 00:05:08,914
A dashboard filter panel, for example.

74
00:05:09,414 --> 00:05:10,794
A query result table.

75
00:05:11,294 --> 00:05:15,624
So this layering matters because it
separates low-level primitives from

76
00:05:15,624 --> 00:05:17,764
product-specific feature modules.

77
00:05:18,224 --> 00:05:21,964
You get to reuse without tight coupling.

78
00:05:22,464 --> 00:05:26,209
And when you do this
well- Three things happen.

79
00:05:26,409 --> 00:05:31,159
You reduce duplication because there's
one implementation per pattern.

80
00:05:31,399 --> 00:05:36,499
You improve maintenance because
changes propagate from a single

81
00:05:36,499 --> 00:05:38,789
source, so it's very easy to maintain.

82
00:05:39,289 --> 00:05:44,349
And you enable parallel development
because teams ship independently

83
00:05:44,399 --> 00:05:45,879
against a shared contract.

84
00:05:46,629 --> 00:05:48,519
Pillar two is token-driven theming.

85
00:05:49,419 --> 00:05:55,249
Design tokens are the contractual layer
between design intent and implementation.

86
00:05:55,759 --> 00:05:59,619
They are the single source of truth
for every visual and interaction

87
00:05:59,619 --> 00:06:05,309
property in the system: color, spacing,
typography, motion, all of that.

88
00:06:05,809 --> 00:06:09,539
The power of tokens is that they
let you make consistent updates

89
00:06:09,539 --> 00:06:14,509
across every analytics surface
without ever touching component code.

90
00:06:15,009 --> 00:06:18,699
You change a token, everything
that ref-- re-everything that

91
00:06:18,699 --> 00:06:20,839
referen-references, it updates.

92
00:06:21,349 --> 00:06:23,719
One change, and it propagates everywhere.

93
00:06:24,219 --> 00:06:30,469
This is huge for analytics platform
because we are constantly tuning things,

94
00:06:30,529 --> 00:06:35,769
adjusting density of a new dashboard
layout, updating a chart color palette

95
00:06:35,769 --> 00:06:40,869
for maybe accessibility, rolling out
a new theme for an embedded view.

96
00:06:41,719 --> 00:06:48,149
Without tokens, those changes mean
hunting through component code and looking

97
00:06:48,149 --> 00:06:52,279
through all the code base to figure
out-- to find the right token to update.

98
00:06:52,779 --> 00:06:57,609
But with tokens, they are single
update at the contract layer, and

99
00:06:57,609 --> 00:07:01,349
it just propagates all over the
system, all of your dashboard.

100
00:07:01,849 --> 00:07:06,189
So now the question is: How does that
token architecture actually work?

101
00:07:07,049 --> 00:07:09,259
You want three levels of abstraction.

102
00:07:10,089 --> 00:07:11,789
Level one is global tokens.

103
00:07:12,069 --> 00:07:17,319
These are your raw design values, hex
codes, pixel scales, font weights, things

104
00:07:17,319 --> 00:07:21,079
like hex color hash two five six three EB.

105
00:07:21,509 --> 00:07:23,849
Just pure values, no meaning attached.

106
00:07:24,349 --> 00:07:26,829
Level two is semantic tokens.

107
00:07:27,059 --> 00:07:31,159
These are purpose-mapped aliases
that point at global tokens.

108
00:07:31,529 --> 00:07:36,539
So instead of hash two five six
three EB, you use color primary.

109
00:07:37,159 --> 00:07:42,969
Instead of sixteen pixel, you
use, say, space dash large or LG.

110
00:07:43,469 --> 00:07:50,869
So instead of a ro-raw value radius,
you use radius MD. So semantic tokens

111
00:07:50,869 --> 00:07:55,819
carry intent, and they make the
system describable in plain language.

112
00:07:56,319 --> 00:07:59,129
Level three is component tokens.

113
00:07:59,709 --> 00:08:05,569
These are scoped to a specific
component, things like button

114
00:08:05,569 --> 00:08:08,369
dash PG or input dash border.

115
00:08:08,889 --> 00:08:13,809
They reference semantic tokens,
which references global tokens This

116
00:08:13,899 --> 00:08:17,849
three-level structure is what gives
you flexibility without the chaos.

117
00:08:18,289 --> 00:08:22,389
You can rethink the global palette
without rewriting every single component.

118
00:08:23,359 --> 00:08:26,399
You can override a semantic
token for a specific team

119
00:08:26,509 --> 00:08:27,979
without touching anything else.

120
00:08:28,789 --> 00:08:32,719
And you can tune a single
component's token without

121
00:08:32,719 --> 00:08:34,179
affecting the rest of the system.

122
00:08:34,739 --> 00:08:38,359
Now, that's the contract
working in your favor.

123
00:08:38,859 --> 00:08:41,969
Pillar three is
cross-platform consistency.

124
00:08:42,709 --> 00:08:45,599
Analytics platforms
don't live in one place.

125
00:08:45,769 --> 00:08:47,609
They span multiple surfaces.

126
00:08:48,019 --> 00:08:52,039
You have standalone dashboard, you
have embedded charts inside other

127
00:08:52,039 --> 00:08:55,899
products, you have operational
tooling for internal teams, and

128
00:08:55,899 --> 00:08:58,339
increasingly you have mobile views.

129
00:08:58,839 --> 00:09:04,419
Achieving coherence across all of these
takes deliberate architectural pattern.

130
00:09:05,289 --> 00:09:06,759
Hope is not a strategy here.

131
00:09:07,279 --> 00:09:11,389
So let me walk you through the
three surfaces I'm thinking about.

132
00:09:11,959 --> 00:09:15,849
Standalone dashboards: this is
the full expression of the design

133
00:09:15,849 --> 00:09:20,639
system, complete layout, navigation,
and data visualization components.

134
00:09:21,439 --> 00:09:25,069
The system gets to show up at its fullest.

135
00:09:26,069 --> 00:09:31,159
Embedded analytics: this is lightweight
token-scoped components that

136
00:09:31,159 --> 00:09:33,299
integrate into host applications.

137
00:09:34,059 --> 00:09:37,709
The constraint here is style isolation.

138
00:09:38,209 --> 00:09:42,699
You can't really bleed your styles
into someone else's product, and you

139
00:09:42,699 --> 00:09:44,739
can't let theirs leak into yours.

140
00:09:45,239 --> 00:09:49,059
Operational tools: these are
density-optimized variants

141
00:09:49,199 --> 00:09:52,839
that share the same component
primitives and token contracts.

142
00:09:53,599 --> 00:09:57,009
Same underlying pieces tuned for
information density and speed.

143
00:09:57,509 --> 00:10:01,259
The key insight is that these
aren't separate design systems.

144
00:10:01,649 --> 00:10:04,749
They are the same system
expressed differently.

145
00:10:05,459 --> 00:10:08,639
The shared parameters and tokens
are what hold them together.

146
00:10:09,139 --> 00:10:13,109
So how do you actually achieve
that coherence in practice?

147
00:10:13,829 --> 00:10:16,569
A few architectural patterns
do most of the work.

148
00:10:17,279 --> 00:10:20,059
At the foundation, you
have a shared token layer.

149
00:10:20,459 --> 00:10:24,249
Every surface, every variant, every
platform anchors to this layer.

150
00:10:25,179 --> 00:10:28,549
That's what makes the system
one thing instead of many.

151
00:10:29,049 --> 00:10:31,829
Above that, you have platform adapters.

152
00:10:31,989 --> 00:10:35,939
These translate the shared token
into runtime-appropriate values

153
00:10:36,409 --> 00:10:37,829
without breaking the contract.

154
00:10:38,509 --> 00:10:44,569
So your tokens compile to CSS variables
on the web-web, native values on

155
00:10:44,569 --> 00:10:48,699
iOS, native values on Android, and
design tool variables in Figma.

156
00:10:49,199 --> 00:10:51,079
Then you have component variants.

157
00:10:51,189 --> 00:10:55,649
The same component expressed
differently for different surfaces.

158
00:10:56,279 --> 00:11:01,439
A button in a density-optimized variant
for operational tools, the same button

159
00:11:01,439 --> 00:11:06,874
full size in a dashboard And on top
of that, surface composi-composition.

160
00:11:07,374 --> 00:11:11,254
How those variants come together
into actual product experiences.

161
00:11:11,754 --> 00:11:15,114
There are also a few key design
decisions worth calling out.

162
00:11:15,224 --> 00:11:18,574
First Shadow DOM and style encapsulation.

163
00:11:18,644 --> 00:11:23,074
When you are embedding into third-party
host, you need real style isolation.

164
00:11:23,524 --> 00:11:25,324
Shadow DOM gives you that.

165
00:11:25,824 --> 00:11:28,154
Second responsive token overrides.

166
00:11:28,564 --> 00:11:32,514
Instead of breakpoint logic
scattered across components, use

167
00:11:33,004 --> 00:11:35,074
viewport-specific token values.

168
00:11:35,584 --> 00:11:36,904
The component doesn't change.

169
00:11:37,404 --> 00:11:41,784
Third, explicit extension points
for product-level variations.

170
00:11:42,444 --> 00:11:47,114
You want pre-product customization
without forking the core

171
00:11:47,284 --> 00:11:49,464
without forking the core system.

172
00:11:50,344 --> 00:11:53,704
Design and extension points
are how you allow that safety.

173
00:11:54,204 --> 00:11:57,114
Pillar four is versioning discipline.

174
00:11:57,744 --> 00:12:00,704
A design system without a
principal versioning strategy

175
00:12:00,704 --> 00:12:02,504
is basically a liability.

176
00:12:03,404 --> 00:12:06,214
I want to be very clear about that.

177
00:12:06,754 --> 00:12:10,294
If consumers don't know what's
going to break when they

178
00:12:10,294 --> 00:12:12,364
upgrade, they stop upgrading.

179
00:12:12,864 --> 00:12:15,994
And once they stop upgrading,
your system is dead in the water.

180
00:12:16,894 --> 00:12:21,284
Semantic versioning paired with
controlled release channels is what

181
00:12:21,284 --> 00:12:24,264
lets a system evolve confidently.

182
00:12:25,254 --> 00:12:29,334
You get to keep moving forward without
silently breaking the downstream

183
00:12:29,334 --> 00:12:31,174
applications that depend on you.

184
00:12:31,674 --> 00:12:37,234
So let me get specific about the
strategies that protect consumers.

185
00:12:38,074 --> 00:12:39,894
First, semantic versioning.

186
00:12:40,824 --> 00:12:45,754
It's major for breaking changes, minor
for new features, patch for fixes.

187
00:12:46,364 --> 00:12:48,014
This contract is explicit.

188
00:12:48,234 --> 00:12:52,104
It's machine-readable, and it lets
dependency tooling do its job.

189
00:12:52,974 --> 00:12:57,764
When a team sees a major version jump,
they know to look at the migration notes.

190
00:12:57,834 --> 00:13:01,004
When they see a patch, they
know they can pull it in safely.

191
00:13:01,994 --> 00:13:04,944
Second, controlled release channels.

192
00:13:05,444 --> 00:13:07,564
Stable or beta releases.

193
00:13:08,094 --> 00:13:11,704
This lets teams opt into
changes at their own pace.

194
00:13:12,304 --> 00:13:17,974
Risk-tolerant teams can run on
surface issues early, and conservative

195
00:13:17,974 --> 00:13:19,924
teams can wait for stable version.

196
00:13:20,424 --> 00:13:22,864
Everyone gets to choose
their level of exposure.

197
00:13:23,364 --> 00:13:26,314
And the third is deprecation workflows.

198
00:13:26,764 --> 00:13:29,544
When something has to go away,
you don't just delete it.

199
00:13:30,324 --> 00:13:32,884
You issue a structured deprecation notice.

200
00:13:32,914 --> 00:13:39,014
You provide a migration guide,
and you give a consuming team

201
00:13:39,014 --> 00:13:41,134
a safe time-bound path forward.

202
00:13:41,574 --> 00:13:46,549
Deprecation is a contract too when you do
these three things well, you can evolve

203
00:13:46,549 --> 00:13:52,509
the system very fast without losing the
trust of the team that depends on you.

204
00:13:53,019 --> 00:14:01,219
Next up is governance maturity, and
arguably the one that determines whether

205
00:14:01,219 --> 00:14:03,389
everything else holds up together.

206
00:14:04,249 --> 00:14:07,799
Governance is what separates a
shared component library from

207
00:14:07,799 --> 00:14:10,409
a true platform capability.

208
00:14:10,619 --> 00:14:13,209
Without it, systems stagnant or fragment.

209
00:14:13,369 --> 00:14:16,049
With it, they compound
in quality over time.

210
00:14:16,549 --> 00:14:22,939
So mature governance has four components:
contribution workflow, where clear

211
00:14:22,939 --> 00:14:26,859
pathways for teams to propose new
components, prototype them, and actually

212
00:14:26,859 --> 00:14:28,769
promote them into the shared system.

213
00:14:29,269 --> 00:14:31,859
People need to actually know
how to contribute and what

214
00:14:31,859 --> 00:14:33,429
happens after they actually do.

215
00:14:33,929 --> 00:14:41,519
Next is review standards, defined criteria
covering API design, any compliance, test

216
00:14:41,519 --> 00:14:43,989
coverage, and documentation completeness.

217
00:14:44,489 --> 00:14:52,089
Last sorry, third, accessibility
enforcement, and this is a non-negotiable.

218
00:14:52,809 --> 00:14:57,279
Automated WCAG checks integrated
into CI pipeline, not left to

219
00:14:57,279 --> 00:14:58,979
my manual audits or goodwill.

220
00:14:59,449 --> 00:15:03,859
If you don't enforce accessibility
automatically, it will not

221
00:15:03,859 --> 00:15:05,359
happen consistently ever.

222
00:15:05,859 --> 00:15:12,059
And the last one is decision frameworks,
documented principles that balance team

223
00:15:12,309 --> 00:15:15,239
autonomy with system alignment at scale.

224
00:15:15,339 --> 00:15:20,409
So when there's a disagreement,
you need a written principle to

225
00:15:20,409 --> 00:15:23,439
fall back on, not just opinions.

226
00:15:23,939 --> 00:15:28,069
Together, these four pieces
are what turn a design system

227
00:15:28,069 --> 00:15:30,109
into a really real platform.

228
00:15:30,609 --> 00:15:36,859
All right, let's go a bit deeper into
the governance because I think this is

229
00:15:36,859 --> 00:15:41,929
where most enterprise design systems
either succeed or they quietly fail.

230
00:15:42,429 --> 00:15:47,319
The most effective governance
model I have seen at scale is what

231
00:15:47,319 --> 00:15:49,479
I would call the federate model.

232
00:15:50,169 --> 00:15:54,939
The idea is that you distribute ownership
while maintaining a shared core.

233
00:15:55,439 --> 00:16:02,889
Platform teams own the foundation, product
teams own their extensions, and there are

234
00:16:02,939 --> 00:16:05,169
clear contribution paths between them.

235
00:16:05,669 --> 00:16:09,159
The platform team owns the
primitives, the tokens, the release

236
00:16:09,159 --> 00:16:12,129
infrastructure, the review standards.

237
00:16:12,749 --> 00:16:16,619
They make sure the core stays
coherent and very high quality.

238
00:16:17,119 --> 00:16:21,899
The product teams contribute
patterns, service surface level

239
00:16:21,969 --> 00:16:23,944
components, and domain extensions.

240
00:16:24,604 --> 00:16:28,824
They know their users best, so they are
the ones building the specific solutions.

241
00:16:29,324 --> 00:16:33,814
But they build on top of a shared
foundation, not next to it.

242
00:16:34,314 --> 00:16:38,824
This federate model is what lets
you scale without bottlenecking.

243
00:16:39,034 --> 00:16:43,644
The platform team can't review every
UI decision every product team makes,

244
00:16:44,244 --> 00:16:48,854
but they can own the contract that
all of those decisions sit on top of.

245
00:16:49,854 --> 00:16:53,334
And product teams get to move
fast inside that contract.

246
00:16:53,834 --> 00:16:59,034
That's the balance, the autonomy
where it speeds people up, alignment

247
00:16:59,034 --> 00:17:00,944
where it keeps the system coherent.

248
00:17:01,444 --> 00:17:05,674
All right, so let me leave you with
five things to take back to your team.

249
00:17:06,314 --> 00:17:09,734
First of all, build on
decoupled primitives.

250
00:17:10,234 --> 00:17:13,494
Modularity is what makes parallel
dev- development and long

251
00:17:13,494 --> 00:17:15,024
term maintainability possible.

252
00:17:15,764 --> 00:17:20,034
If your primitives are tangled,
everything above them will be too.

253
00:17:20,534 --> 00:17:23,734
Second tokens are your source of truth.

254
00:17:24,004 --> 00:17:28,924
Visual and interaction properties belong
in tokens, not hard-coded in components.

255
00:17:29,504 --> 00:17:31,994
The contract layer is
where consistency lives.

256
00:17:32,494 --> 00:17:35,424
Third design for all
surfaces from day one.

257
00:17:35,984 --> 00:17:40,174
Cross-platform coherence is an
architectural decision, not a retrofit.

258
00:17:40,974 --> 00:17:43,854
Retrofitting is always more
expensive than planning ahead.

259
00:17:44,354 --> 00:17:47,054
Fourth, version with intent.

260
00:17:47,554 --> 00:17:50,384
Semantic versioning and
release channels protect your

261
00:17:50,384 --> 00:17:52,544
consumers and your credibility.

262
00:17:52,654 --> 00:17:56,294
Without them, no one trusts the
system enough to depend on it.

263
00:17:57,294 --> 00:18:02,044
And the last one is invest in
governance before you need it.

264
00:18:02,594 --> 00:18:06,644
Contribution workflows and
accessibility enforcement are what let

265
00:18:06,644 --> 00:18:08,664
a system scale without fragmenting.

266
00:18:09,524 --> 00:18:12,454
By the time you obviously need
governance, the cost of adding

267
00:18:12,454 --> 00:18:14,724
it has already gone way up high.

268
00:18:15,224 --> 00:18:19,744
Put these five together and you
have got a design system that

269
00:18:19,744 --> 00:18:23,584
can actually keep pace with a
high-performance analytics platform.

270
00:18:24,084 --> 00:18:28,234
One that holds up across teams,
across surfaces, and across time.

271
00:18:29,234 --> 00:18:30,324
That's pretty amazing.

272
00:18:30,824 --> 00:18:33,004
And yeah, that's it from me.

